/wiki/Sporting_CP_(futsal): Sporting Clube de Portugal has a professional futsal team based in Lisbon, Portugal, since 4 March 1985, and plays in Portuguese Futsal First Division. They are the most decorated team in terms of domestic titles in the country, and are the current European champions. Having made the last 10 finals and winning 7, Sporting have won 3 straight Portuguese championships on two occasions.
/wiki/Grupo_Desportivo_Estoril_Praia: Grupo Desportivo Estoril Praia (Portuguese pronunciation: [(ɨ)ʃtuˈɾiɫ ˈpɾajɐ]), commonly known as Estoril, is a Portuguese sports club from Estoril, Cascais, Lisbon. Founded on 17 May 1939, its football team currently plays in LigaPro and hold home games at the Estádio António Coimbra da Mota, with a seating capacity of 8,015. As a sports club, Estoril has departments for football, futsal and basketball.
/wiki/Santos_da_Venda_Nova: Santos Futebol Clube da Venda Nova is a Portuguese sports club based in Venda Nova, Amadora. Founded in 1982 the club is better known for its futsal team whose greatest success was winning the second edition of the Portuguese Futsal League. After last playing in the top tier during the 2001–02 season following two promotions in two seasons, the futsal team currently plays in the local Liga Futsal Inatel Lisboa amateur league.
/wiki/Atl\u00e9tico_Clube_de_Portugal: Atlético Clube de Portugal is a Portuguese club, located in the city of Lisbon, more precisely in the parish of Alcântara. It was founded on September 18, 1942 due to the merger of two clubs of Alcântara (Carcavelinhos Football Club) and Santo Amaro (União Foot-Ball Lisboa). Besides Football, the club also has sections of Futsal and Basketball. In the past the club had sections of Field Hockey, Swimming, Sport Fishing, Cycle-Touring, Table Tennis, Rugby, Volleyball, Gymnastics, Triathlon and Handball.
/wiki/1993\u201394_Campeonato_Nacional_d: The 1993–94 season of the Liga Portuguesa de Futsal was the 4th season of top-tier futsal in Portugal. The season started on September 22, 1993, and ended on June 4, 1994. Sporting CP won the competition for the third time in total and the second time in a row, making it the first time a team won back-to-back futsal national championships in Portugal. Santo Tirso withdrew halfway through the season, as such the games the team had played for the league didn't count towards the final standings and every team had a bye on the second half of the season.
/wiki/Grupo_Desportivo_e_Cultural_do_Cor: Grupo Desportivo e Cultural do Correio da Manhã was a Portuguese sports club based in Lisbon. Founded in 1981 by employees of the newspaper Correio da Manhã, the club was better known for its futsal team whose greater successes included two Portuguese Futsal League wins and one Portuguese Futsal Cup. The futsal team ceased playing after the 2003–04 season ceding its spot in the league to Estrela da Amadora.
/wiki/Miramar_Futsal_Clube: Miramar Futsal Clube was a Portuguese futsal club from Valadares, Vila Nova de Gaia. Founded in 1991 the club won two Portuguese Futsal Leagues and competed on the last edition of the Futsal European Clubs Championship. The team was dissolved after the 2007–08 season.
/wiki/AR_Freixieiro: Associação Recreativa de Freixieiro is a professional futsal team based in Matosinhos, Portugal. It plays in the II Divisão Futsal.
/wiki/S.L._Benfica_(futsal): Sport Lisboa e Benfica, commonly known as Benfica, is a professional futsal team based in Lisbon, Portugal, that plays in the Liga Portuguesa de Futsal, where they are the current champions.
/wiki/Funda\u00e7\u00e3o_Jorge_Antunes: Fundação Jorge Antunes Is a professional futsal team based in Vizela, Portugal. It plays in Portuguese Futsal First Division.
/wiki/S.L._Olivais_(futsal): Sport Lisboa e Olivais is an amateur futsal team based in Lisbon, Portugal. It plays in Portuguese Futsal First Division.
/wiki/2006\u201307_Campeonato_Nacional_d: The 2006–07 season of the Portuguese Futsal First Division was the 17th season of top-tier futsal in Portugal, and was won by Benfica.
/wiki/C.F._Os_Belenenses_(futsal): Clube Futebol Os Belenenses is an amateur futsal team based in Lisbon, Portugal. It plays in Liga Placard .
/wiki/2008\u201309_Campeonato_Nacional_d: The 2008–09 season of the Portuguese Futsal First Division was the 19th season of top-tier futsal in Portugal and it was won by Benfica.
/wiki/2009\u201310_Campeonato_Nacional_d: The 2009–10 season of the Portuguese Futsal First Division is the 20th season of top-tier futsal in Portugal.
/wiki/Instituto_D._Jo\u00e3o_V: Instituto D. João V was a former futsal team from Pombal, Portugal. They played in Liga Portuguesa de Futsal but closed in 2011 due to lack of sponsors.
